Your solution is close, but you&#39;re using `nextLine()` on the Scanner which will consume the entire String data all at once.

I modified your code a little and produced this output:
```
[[B, B, S], [S, B, F], [B, B, F], [3, null, null], [null, null, null]]
```
It&#39;s not totally clear what you&#39;re trying to do, but I think this should give you some ideas for how to fix it. I changed a few things for this example:

- define the `Scanner` to use the input you&#39;ve specified (instead of prompting for it)
- rename the `Scanner` variable from `str` to `scanner`; makes the rest of the code more readable
- rename `num` variable to `charactersPerLine`, better readability
- use `scanner.next()` instead of `nextLine()`, that way you&#39;ll get &quot;B&quot;, then &quot;B&quot;, then &quot;S&quot;, etc. each as a separate string value
- added a guard if the scanner is empty, then eject; this is probably something you won&#39;t need to keep but I added it so my example works
- print the entire array at the end

```
public static void main(String[] args) {
    Scanner scanner = new Scanner(&quot;3 B B S S B F B B F 3&quot;);
    int charactersPerLine = scanner.nextInt();
    String[][] dice = new String[5][charactersPerLine];

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; 5; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j &lt; charactersPerLine; j++) {
            if (!scanner.hasNext()) {
                break;
            }
            dice[i][j] = scanner.next();
        }
    }

    System.out.println(Arrays.deepToString(dice));
}
```

**Update**:  The newline-delimited input in OP was added after I posted this answer, but it doesn&#39;t change the behavior. Whether or not there are newlines, `scanner.next()` will still return the next value. This input – which includes newlines – still produces the same behavior:
```
Scanner scanner = new Scanner(&quot;3\n&quot; +
        &quot;B B S\n&quot; +
        &quot;S B F\n&quot; +
        &quot;B B F&quot;);
```

