 ```

In particular, since you&#39;re already correctly observing the `response`, you can simply check which is the response type:

``` lang-typescript
this.http.get(&#39;http://localhost:8080/getColors&#39;, this.requestOptions)
.pipe(
  map(response =&gt; !response.ok ? 
                  throw new Error(&#39;Request error, reponse code: &#39; + response.status : 
                  response[&#39;body&#39;])
);
```

Note that throwing an Error inside a `map` will cause the observable to error, and so you can deal with it on your code that calls the request like so:

``` lang-typescript
this.service.getColors().pipe(
  catchError((error) =&gt; /* do something with that error */
);
```

All that said, you did ask for *best practices* dealing with this. In that case, I recommend looking into [Http Interceptors][1] if you want to deal with all Http responses in a similar manner(like logging them somewhere, or showing a tooltip informing the user that a request failed, etc). Interceptors enable you to create module-wide or even app-wide behavior over all responses called from within a module/the app.


  [1]: https://angular.io/api/common/http/HttpInterceptor

